19:53.405 --> 20:00.975
But when you look at the judgment and wrath of God and the Bible and then you consider like this mercy and grace, they can seem like opposite, antithetical.

20:01.035 --> 20:14.834
And then it can confirm, depending on where you come from and your experience is life, it can kind of confirm some ideas, imaginations that you have of God that he's this mean God that's just eager to condemn, eager to put you down.

20:15.362 --> 20:18.545
For many, this is what you imagine God to be, this angry, judging God.

20:19.886 --> 20:25.092
For others, we respond opposite of that, and we just imagine it to be this peace and love in God.

20:25.132 --> 20:30.997
And so here we find both brought together, but first it's the judgment.

20:32.118 --> 20:33.199
And his judgment is good.

20:33.219 --> 20:44.050
I mean, do you really want to follow a God who sees evil in this world and just ignores it and excuses it?

20:45.250 --> 20:45.951
Of course not.

20:47.513 --> 20:53.562
At the bare minimum, you want a God who's going to be at least as mad at the injustices in this world as you are, right?

20:55.024 --> 20:59.491
And if he's really a Just God, he's going to be more angry at these things, because there are no front to him.

21:00.793 --> 21:09.446
And if we are indeed guilty of sin against him, of crime, of treason against God, doesn't he have a right towards judgment towards it?

21:11.248 --> 21:14.994
I mean, wouldn't it be weird for him not to bring judgment towards sin?

21:16.098 --> 21:22.148
Further, would you really want him to ignore the guilt of others like you want him to ignore the guilt of you?

21:22.169 --> 21:32.546
I think at the end of the day, we know that this is true, that God has to come and he has to judge the wrong and the wicked and this is what we want him to do.

21:33.488 --> 21:39.218
We know we can't hide from this, but sometimes we think, man, maybe if I just don't think about it, he won't think about it.

21:40.578 --> 21:46.026
And then when he delays judgment and brings stuff out in our lives, that delay can make us think that, oh, maybe he forgot about it too.

21:47.127 --> 21:48.189
But God is patient.

21:49.030 --> 21:49.631
He is slow.

21:50.412 --> 21:53.957
Like in 22 years, his brothers have not been struck down.

21:55.579 --> 21:57.842
God is patient.

21:57.862 --> 22:00.085
But God's patience in our lives is not indifference.

22:01.707 --> 22:03.570
His patience is not him ignoring

22:05.378 --> 22:06.880
You cannot escape judgment.

22:06.980 --> 22:07.420
He waits.

22:07.480 --> 22:10.664
He draws us out so that our guilt can be rightly judged.

22:12.486 --> 22:14.067
I think this is what Judah understands here.

22:14.087 --> 22:14.888
He doesn't minimize it.

22:14.908 --> 22:16.450
He says, well, so what can I say?

22:16.510 --> 22:17.611
I don't have a defense.

22:18.252 --> 22:24.098
I'm guilty, which begs the question, what does it mean for us to face judgment when we are guilty?

22:24.899 --> 22:25.960
What does that look like for us?

22:26.681 --> 22:31.446
We say that exposure and judgment are good, but how are they good when we're guilty?

22:33.248 --> 22:35.250
How can we endure the punishment of our guilt?

22:36.098 --> 22:37.760
to be free from the weight of guilt.

22:37.780 --> 22:38.481
How does this happen?

22:38.561 --> 22:40.483
At the end of the day, you can't on your own.

22:42.025 --> 22:49.995
Romans tells us that the wages of sin is death, which is the judgment that you have for your sin is death.

22:50.035 --> 22:51.497
The judgment for your guilt is death.

22:52.218 --> 22:53.259
It's not very encouraging.

22:53.279 --> 23:00.368
It sure seems like if that's the outcome of judgment, then maybe we want to stay hiding then.

23:01.329 --> 23:02.290
What do we do with this?

23:03.586 --> 23:06.370
But this is exactly why hiding is so destructive.

23:06.410 --> 23:08.573
Because when we hide, we aren't just avoiding judgment.

23:08.593 --> 23:10.275
We're actually playing judge.

23:10.295 --> 23:13.099
We think it's not big enough deal to bring this out into the open.

23:13.119 --> 23:14.380
We're just going to carry ourselves.

23:15.222 --> 23:20.368
But the reality is you can't, and in fact, you have actually already been judged.

23:21.930 --> 23:25.615
The only way you can be free from your guilt is by letting the judgment come.

23:27.057 --> 23:29.000
Judgment will fall and it must fall.

23:29.020 --> 23:33.586
The question, the turn here, is the question is where is that judgment going to fall?

23:34.722 --> 23:37.125
I mean, this is the profound beauty of this chapter.

23:39.508 --> 23:45.235
In the beauty of the gospel, the God exposes our sin so he can judge it and lead us into healing.

23:45.255 --> 23:49.220
And that healing comes as the judgment falls not on you, not on me, but on God himself.

23:50.481 --> 23:53.305
You see, his mercy and grace do not come apart from judgment.

23:54.747 --> 23:57.350
But the mercy and grace of God come actually through judgment.

23:58.311 --> 24:02.456
Let's see these are the final thing we see here about how God deals with our guilt.

24:02.476 --> 24:04.018
That God provides his substitute.

24:04.386 --> 24:04.887
for our guilt.

24:05.968 --> 24:09.111
Due to second speech, leads to this moment.

24:09.131 --> 24:11.054
It's openness, honest, and it leads to this.

24:11.814 --> 24:17.461
It's kind of all summarizing what's happened to lead to this moment in verse 32 and 33.

24:17.501 --> 24:26.951
It says, for your servant became a pledge of safety for the boy to my father, saying, if I do not bring him back to you, then I shall bear the blame before my father all my life.

24:28.513 --> 24:32.818
Now, therefore, please let your servant remain instead of the boy as a servant to my Lord.

24:33.314 --> 24:35.457
and let the boy go back with his brothers.

24:38.582 --> 24:45.072
We saw in the last chapter, Judah, telling his dad, listen, I will be a pledge for my brother.

24:45.993 --> 24:54.927
And now in the face of danger, in the face of his life being sold into service for the rest of his life, what is he who stands in that place and he says, I will be a substitute.

24:56.029 --> 24:59.213
He says, let me bear the punishment for what Benjamin has done.

25:00.495 --> 25:02.258
This is a crucial piece here.

25:03.362 --> 25:05.705
Judah is not asking for judgment to be erased.

25:06.325 --> 25:07.707
He's not saying, hey, can we just forget about this?

25:07.767 --> 25:08.167
Move on.

25:08.247 --> 25:09.248
It's not that big of a deal, bro.

25:09.328 --> 25:11.070
You got lots of silver cups, probably.

25:12.952 --> 25:14.454
He's not asking for judgment to be erased.

25:14.474 --> 25:16.116
He's asking for it to be redirected.

25:17.537 --> 25:20.781
See, guilt does not actually disappear here.

25:22.022 --> 25:25.005
It's transferred from one party to the other.

25:26.387 --> 25:30.351
From Benjamin, his guilt has been asked to be given to Judah.

25:31.412 --> 25:33.234
And I think this is one of the

25:35.298 --> 25:40.403
One of the profound aspects of judgment that falls here.

25:42.585 --> 25:45.088
And this is one of the things I think that we struggle with with the cross.

25:45.769 --> 25:48.111
Sometimes we wonder, did you just really have to die?

25:48.652 --> 25:50.173
Couldn't have God just forgiven us?

25:51.314 --> 25:54.077
This whole son of God dying thing is a little excessive.

25:54.097 --> 25:55.899
I actually have some books on my bookshelf.

25:56.420 --> 25:57.601
They're not like ones I'd recommend.

25:58.041 --> 26:02.706
Talk about the death of Christ, like it's divine child abuse.

26:03.202 --> 26:06.066
Like it's such a mean and dark and weird thing for him to do.

26:06.887 --> 26:11.693
Some people struggle with the cross because of this, but in this moment here, it helps us see the truth.

26:11.753 --> 26:12.494
And what's at stake?

26:12.514 --> 26:13.995
That sin cannot go unjudged.

26:14.055 --> 26:15.617
The guilty cannot go unjudged.

26:16.699 --> 26:19.202
I mean, we don't want the evil in this world to go unjudged.

26:19.262 --> 26:22.826
Someone has to pay for that guilt.

26:22.846 --> 26:23.567
Let me give you a scenario.

26:23.627 --> 26:25.970
Imagine someone steals $500 from me.

26:27.773 --> 26:30.916
And they come and you find out and they're like, hey, you know, I'm really sorry, I just needed money.

26:31.357 --> 26:32.178
Will you forgive me?

26:32.610 --> 26:35.654
And they say, and you say to them, yeah, I forgive you.

26:35.774 --> 26:36.715
You could have just asked me.

26:37.636 --> 26:41.941
But since you need that money, I'll forgive you, and I'll let you keep that $500.

26:43.824 --> 26:45.225
Very generous of that person, right?

26:45.746 --> 26:48.429
You're still generous for letting someone who's still $500 keep that money.

26:48.850 --> 26:49.250
Good job.

26:49.991 --> 26:52.915
But that forgiveness doesn't erase the cost.

26:54.917 --> 26:56.319
Forgiveness always costs something.

26:58.241 --> 26:59.042
Just who does it cost?

26:59.122 --> 27:00.524
It costs the person who forgave the $500.

27:00.564 --> 27:02.066
They're still out $500.

27:02.530 --> 27:03.652
The wages of sin is death.

27:06.556 --> 27:09.760
The guilty, it always leads to death, the sin cost death.

27:10.661 --> 27:13.285
And the wonder of the gospel is this, that God became flesh, right?

27:13.305 --> 27:21.757
Judah's descendant is Christ himself who came as a pledge for you to say, listen, you are guilty, put your guilt on me.

27:21.817 --> 27:25.342
He will take your guilt on himself.

27:26.343 --> 27:29.387
He will die the death that is owed to you.

27:29.427 --> 27:31.250
He takes on himself.

27:32.034 --> 27:37.542
And not only do we give Him our sin, He gives us His perfection and righteousness to you.

27:39.946 --> 27:47.297
That sin you are hiding from right now, for fear of judgment, He's already been dealt with.

27:50.362 --> 27:54.047
The sting of death has been removed by Christ.

27:54.128 --> 27:58.354
Does He conquer sin, rising to new life?

27:59.394 --> 28:01.017
The sting of death has been removed.

28:01.057 --> 28:03.922
The sting of your judgment for your sin is no more.

28:04.483 --> 28:04.984
It's gone.

28:06.507 --> 28:07.168
You know what this means?

28:07.208 --> 28:10.855
There's nothing left to fear in your confession of sin.

28:12.178 --> 28:13.400
There's nothing left to hide.

28:14.582 --> 28:17.307
And this truth is wildly freeing.

28:18.970 --> 28:23.218
And the challenge for us is to step out in faith to trust it.

28:24.354 --> 28:28.698
to trust that Christ has paid for our guilt, that it has fallen on Him.

28:28.799 --> 28:37.187
And the challenge for us as a community is to believe that and live that out when someone confesses their sin, that our first reply is, there's now no condemnation for you.

28:37.668 --> 28:38.929
It's not, whoa, you did what?

28:40.190 --> 28:46.837
That might come at some point, or at least in your head you might think that, but how words we say to each other are, there's no condemnation for you.

28:47.998 --> 28:51.602
It creates a wildly humble community that says, listen, I'm not better than anybody.

28:52.066 --> 28:53.528
I'm just as guilty as you.

28:53.608 --> 28:56.392
Jesus had to die for me just as much as he had to die for you.

28:56.453 --> 28:59.457
There's no like balancing scale there.

28:59.497 --> 29:02.221
This is a profound truth.

29:04.324 --> 29:07.429
The Christ took the judgment that was owed to us on himself.

29:09.051 --> 29:10.353
You have nothing left to prove.

29:11.976 --> 29:14.219
If you have faith in Christ, you are forgiven.

29:14.279 --> 29:15.181
You are free.

29:16.563 --> 29:20.428
And if you don't have faith in Christ, it's as simple as saying Christ, I've have faith in you.

29:20.509 --> 29:21.490
I believe in you.

29:22.626 --> 29:23.107
And he will.

29:24.449 --> 29:26.331
He will become a pledge for you.

29:26.992 --> 29:28.414
He will give you his righteousness.

29:28.454 --> 29:30.497
He will make you perfect here and now.

29:33.101 --> 29:37.728
And as he does this to us, he grows us into humble people that share this grace with each other.

29:37.768 --> 29:41.713
As we share this mercy and grace with each other, we share it with the world.

29:43.616 --> 29:48.824
May we grow into be this kind of people who trust the freedom that we have in Christ.

29:49.364 --> 29:50.546
Trusting our guilt.

29:52.386 --> 29:52.686
to Him.

29:54.549 --> 29:54.989
Pray with me.

29:57.312 --> 30:00.416
Merciful God in heaven, we give you thanks for your goodness.

30:02.319 --> 30:06.384
We give you thanks for the beauty of the gospel that you have taken all our guilt.

30:08.566 --> 30:14.754
All the heinous things that we've done and will do you've taken unto yourself, that we might have life in you.

30:15.796 --> 30:20.882
I pray that you would help us to trust this truth, that we live in light of this truth,

30:21.954 --> 30:26.681
So it would be a joyously repenting people that trust your grace is enough.

30:27.989 --> 30:28.874
I pray this in your holy name.

30:29.236 --> 30:29.618
Amen.

